# Version Control Practices

## Commit Messages
- Write clear, concise commit messages
- Start with a verb in imperative mood (Add, Fix, Update, Remove, etc.)
- Keep the first line under 50 characters
- If needed, add more details after a blank line

## Branching
- Use feature branches for new development
- Follow Git Flow or similar branching strategy:
  - `main`: Production-ready code
  - `develop`: Development branch
  - `feature/<name>`: New features
  - `bugfix/<name>`: Bug fixes
  - `release/<version>`: Release preparation

## Pull Requests
- Create pull requests for code review before merging
- Keep PRs focused and of manageable size
- Include appropriate tests
- Reference related issues

## General Practices
- Keep commits focused and atomic
- Follow semantic versioning for releases
- Don't commit generated files or credentials
- Regularly pull from the main branch to stay up-to-date
